  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Freddie Freeman Walks Off Los Angeles Angels",
    "subheadline": "Los Angeles Dodgers 1, Los Angeles Angels 0.",
    "lead_angle": "Freddie Freeman launched a Kirby Yates fastball deep into the right field seats, a solo shot in the ninth inning that gave the Los Angeles Dodgers a walk-off 1-0 victory over the Los Angeles Angels. The thunderous blast off the Angels’ closer ended a tense, scoreless duel, sending the UNIQLO Field faithful into a frenzy and crediting Dodgers reliever Blake Treinen with the hard-fought win after a clean top of the ninth.\n\nThe game remained locked in a scoreless tie entering the final frame, largely due to Angels starter Roki Sasaki's brilliant effort. Sasaki had baffled Dodgers bats through seven innings, allowing no runs and fanning ten. After his departure, the Angels bullpen held firm through the eighth, with Kirby Yates taking the mound in the ninth to face the heart of the Dodgers order, an inning after his counterpart, Blake Treinen, had dispatched the Angels quietly.\n\nFreeman stood as the clear offensive difference-maker for either side, collecting two hits, including his game-winning homer, and the only RBI of the afternoon. This tight Freeway Series triumph carries significant weight for the Dodgers, who continue to jostle for position in a tight divisional race. The Angels, despite Sasaki's masterful performance on the mound, find themselves losing crucial ground in the wild card chase, left to ponder what might have been.",
    "reason": "Walk-offs are baseball's signature drama. The season's best finish this day."
  },
